{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f4901c54-2dca-44f7-995b-2dadedcbf223","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs (`CLRLoad` logs from `mscoree.dll`) diagnose problems like:\n\n- Wrong .NET runtime version being loaded\n- Runtime failing to load entirely\n- Unexpected .NET 3.5 Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n- Multiple CLR versions loaded into one process\n\nThey won't help with a `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**To diagnose your crash, I'd recommend:**\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line has the null reference.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception debugging** in your IDE.\n3. **Collect a crash dump** — I can help with that if needed.\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or source code you'd like me to look at?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00b8b26c-2398-426c-a9e4-655c9e358e57","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there are any relevant files in the working directory first, and also consider whether the CLR activation debugging skill would be helpful here.\n\nWait - the user is asking about CLR activation logs, but a NullReferenceException is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with runtime loading/selection issues (e.g., wrong runtime version, failed to load runtime, etc.), not application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException.\n\nLet me first check what's in the working directory to understand the context better.","outputTokens":357},"id":"ce5002e7-d98f-4dab-9dfa-4bdd8580c4fd","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:15:16.957Z","parentId":"e95268e6-e233-4bbc-bd39-06f34e2b51c0"}
